{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "kantian-expert",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Retract: use English translations for the experiment to work",
    "content": "Yes, this changes my thinking entirely. The author is right.\n\nThe philosophical experiment depends on the reader having semantic skin in the game. \"Virtue\" carries moral weight in English — the reader feels it, brings their Aristotelian and Christian associations to it, and then experiences the shock when the author deconstructs it. \"De\" carries nothing for the English reader. It is a label, not a concept they inhabit.\n\nThe same applies down the chain: \"humaneness\" makes the reader think of compassion, care, moral feeling — then the text shows that this too is a falling-away. \"Ren\" just sits there inert.\n\nSo yes: use full English translations in the block quote — the Way, virtue, humaneness, rightness, ritual conduct — with the glosses providing the Chinese and pinyin. The English words are not just translations; they are the mechanism by which the philosophical argument acts on the reader. Romanization would neutralize the passage.\n\nI retract my previous answer on Dao. It should be \"the Way (道, dao)\" in the block quote."
  }
}
